---
syntax: bash
tags: [bash, personal, file-system, monitoring]
version: 1.0.0
---

NAME
    fswatch - Monitor file system changes

SYNOPSIS
    fswatch [options] [path...]

DESCRIPTION
    fswatch is a file change monitor that receives notifications when the contents of specified files or directories are modified. It can watch one or more files or directories and execute a command when they change.

OPTIONS
    -0, --print0             Use the ASCII NUL character (\0) as line separator
    -1, --one-event          Exit after the first event is received
    -e, --exclude=REGEX      Exclude paths matching REGEX
    -E, --extended           Use extended regular expressions
    -i, --include=REGEX      Include paths matching REGEX
    -L, --follow-links       Follow symbolic links
    -m, --monitor=NAME       Use the specified monitor (inotify, kqueue, etc.)
    -o, --one-per-batch      Print a single message with the number of change events
    -r, --recursive          Recurse subdirectories
    -t, --timestamp          Print the event timestamp
    -x, --event-flags        Print the event flags
    --event-flag-separator=STRING  Use STRING to separate event flags
    --format=FORMAT          Use the specified format string to print events
    --batch-marker=STRING    Print STRING to mark the end of a batch of events
    -v, --verbose            Print verbose output
    -h, --help               Show help message
    --version                Show version information

USAGE
    fswatch [options] [path...] | xargs -n 1 -I {} command {}

EXAMPLES
    fswatch -o /path/to/watch | xargs -n 1 -I {} echo {}
    fswatch -or /path/to/watch | xargs -n 1 sh -c 'echo "$0 changed"'

OUTPUT
    By default, fswatch prints the path of each changed file or directory to stdout.

BREAKDOWN
fswatch is a separate utility. It's commonly used in bash scripts to trigger actions based on file system changes. The command monitors specified paths and can execute actions when changes occur.
